Package com.cafean.client.ui

Class GenericTMColumn

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cafean.client.ui.GenericTMColumn
  • public class GenericTMColumn
extends java.lang.Object
    A column for use with a GenericTableModel. Instances of this class act as a container which holds data retrieval, update, and cell-editable methods for a column of data within a GenericTableModel. Columns may optionally be associated with a PropertyContextType which dialogs may query to locate which column a particular context object applies to. The next few sections discuss the pluggable functionality of a GenericTMColumn.

    Providing Row Retrieval and Setting Functionality:
    GenericTMColumns use a Function for accessing column values at a particular row-index. The row index is passed into the function, and the Column value is expected in return.
    Similarly, GenericTMColumns use a BiConsumer for setting column values at a particular row-index. The BiConsumer will be given the row-index and the new value to set.


    Providing isCellEditable Logic:
    GenericTMColumns use a Predicate for determining whether or not a value in a particular column is editable. This Predicate takes the row-index and returns a boolean indicating the editable status.


    Context Associations:
    Views can be associated with ExportContext instances which denote some additional action that should occur (providing an initial selection on open for example). GenericTMColumns can optionally be associated with a PropertyContextType, which can be queried by UI elements to find a corresponding column that matches a PropertyContextType that the UI element was configured with.

    The GenericTMColumn matches PropertyContextTypes with the isContextType method. By default, context types are matched by identity (==) but this can be overridden by providing a different comparing function. The comparing function should examine two given PropertyContextTypes and return true if they match. It may be necessary to provide a comparing function for columns that are dynamically generated at run-time rather than being a static definition, since UI elements will need to be dynamic in how they are looking for appropriate context types. An example of this would be for columns that are generated through introspection.

        public boolean isContextType​(PropertyContextType type)
        Examines a given PropertyContextType to determine if it matches this column's PropertyContextType. This method will compare the two types through the comparing function that was set on this column, or through simple identity equivalence (==) by default.
        Parameters:
        type - the type to compare with
        Returns:
        true if the types match, false otherwise

      • setContextComparingFunction

        public void setContextComparingFunction​(java.util.function.BiFunction<PropertyContextType,​PropertyContextType,​java.lang.Boolean> comparingFunction)
        Sets the comparing function used in isContextType. By default, the comparing function is a simple identity function. This is useful for columns whose context types should be matched by something other than identity (i.e., for columns whose context type is generated at run-time and is not static - they can be matched by something like a column name).
        Parameters:
        comparingFunction - the comparing function
